<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
Place a footnote number in your text immediately after the cited material. This number directs your reader to a footnote at the bottom of your page containing details of the classical reference.
<br>
<blockquote>
	<div class="in-text-citation">
		Seamus Heaney translates the opening lines of Beowulf &#34;So. The Spear&#45;Danes in days gone by and the kings who ruled them had courage and greatness.&#34;<sup>1</sup>
	</div>
	<br>
	<div class="in-text-citation">
		The poet Ovid describes a statue coming to life.<sup>2</sup>
	</div>
	<br>
	<div class="in-text-citation">
		For Irenaeus the end of humanity consists in beholding God.<sup>3</sup>
	</div>
</blockquote>
<br>
<strong>FOOTNOTES</strong>
<br><br>
<blockquote>
	<div class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
		1. <em>Beowulf</em>, trans. Seamus Heaney. (London: Faber, 1999).
	</div>
	<div class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
		2. Ovid, Met. 10.6.270.
	</div>
	<div class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
		3. Irenaeus, <em>Adversus haereses</em>. 4.34.5&#45;7.
	</div>
</blockquote>
